bug.short_desc: namespace branch: qx.ui.table context menu checkmark overlays text

long_desc.thetext:
If the context menue of a qx.ui.table is opened and a row is deselected here to not be displayed anymore (the checkmark is removed) the next time the context menue is opened all remaining checkmarks are displayed above the column name.
This is visible in all demo file eg. demo/Table_1.html.
A screen snapshot is attached which shows the effect.
Created attachment 4 screen snapshot which shows the bug
qx.ui.table is developed by Til Schneider

The width of the "check" icon and the width of the "unchecked" icon were different. The menu code is recomputing the width of only the changed icon, not all icons (looking for the maximum width). This fixes the bug, but there is likely an underlying issue that should be fixed as well. The maximum width of the whole set of icons in a menu should be computed each time an icon state changes.

Sebastian, I'm reassigning to you, to look at the menu issue I "fixed" in comment 3. Do you want to close this bug as is, create a new bug for the possible menu problem described, or leave this open to fix that problem?
Oops. I didn't mention the check-in that fixes it. 3367 (theme.js and new icon menu-blank.gif)

Thank you for you analysis, but I think you are wrong.
The problem is not the menu layouter. It handle this check/uncheck correctly as you can see in more simple examples (without a table widget). Also without the images, you've added to SVN. I don't think we need them. The next time you thought there is a bug somewhere, please try to keep the test example as small as possible and just test the basic stuff. These images are not needed. I think it would be the best to revert your changes.
It's IMO related to the manual flush of the queues inside the table widget. Currently it's not possible to get dynamic dimensions at any time, this is a general layout issue. But the work-around inside the table, to flush the queues, break other stuff as well and seems not to be a good idea.
Back assigned to Til :)

Having had additional discussion with Sebastian on this, the current solution is the wrong medium- and long-term solution. In the medium term, the use of queue flushing in the Table code should be revisited and eliminated. Sebastian believes that will solve this bug. In the long-term, the layout system will be rewritten, allowing (among other things) obtaining dymanically calculated dimensions at any time.
For time very short term, check-in 3367, affecting theme.js and the added blank image, allows the code to be used. As soon as the medium-term solution is ready, the changes to theme.js in check-in 3367 should be reverted and (unless there's some other need for it), the new blank image removed.
Til, if I have time to work on this before you do, can you explain why you need the queue flushes, and where you'd suggest I look for a fix to this problem that does not require the queue flushes?

> Til, if I have time to work on this before you do, can you explain why you need > the queue flushes, and where you'd suggest I look for a fix to this problem > that does not require the queue flushes?
There are three calls of Widget.flushGlobalQueues in the table API:
In Table._updateScrollerWidths the call might be obsolete.
In TablePaneScroller._modifyHorizontalScrollBarVisible the call is needed to ensure _updateContent can work with correct widget sizes (as the comment explains).
In TablePaneScroller._showResizeLine the call is needed in order to get the correct size of the _paneClipper.
I have checked this: When hiding a column only _updateScrollerWidths is called. So the other calls of Widget.flushGlobalQueues are irrelevant for this bug. And if I comment out the call, the bug is still there. Thus the calls of Widget.flushGlobalQueues are not the reason for that bug.
So the next step should be a small test page that tries to reproduce the bug. This should help to find the real cause.
Thank you for the fix. The context menu is working now as expected.

Not quite fixed. Works for Firefox and IE if table is created by left/right values and works in Firefox if table is created by left/width values. Currently the column menu displays in the wrong place in IE if the tale is created by left/width values.
Ok, now it's working in IE even with the table created by left/width instead of left/right parameters.
